         <div type="apparatus">
           <listApp>
            <app><note>Upright lines indicate block ends. Restoration of the entablature appears to indicate that the whole ttext was contained on these three blocks, although the absence of names for those represented by the statues is surprising.</note></app>
           </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>According to the decision of Iunius Maximus the eminent Quaestor,<supplied reason="lost">Gr</supplied>ypos son of Artemidoros restored the two statues .</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>For the quaestor, Junius Maximus, see <title>PIR</title>2 I 0774, and G. Alföldy/H. Halfman <title>ZPE</title> 35 (1979), 195f.,  Reynolds, <title>Aphrodisias Papers</title> 2, 19.  As tribune in 165-6 he brought news of vistory in Partia to Rome, and was rewarded by the quaestorship held in Asia in 167-8. This text suggests that he was treated there as one whose actions conferred éclat on those involved with him, since  the Aphrodisians seem to have invited his judgement on a matter on which, as far as we know, they were under no obligation to do so</p>
            <p>  Grypos son of Artemidoros belonged to a family attested as active in the city from the Flavian period to the late second century CE, but at present we have no other record of his activities.</p>
            <p>The statues restored may have had names on their bases, or possibly represented not persons but deities or concepts too obvious to need them.</p>
         </div>
